DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20321010
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20321011
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:firstadvent-2032@christian
SUMMARY:First Sunday of Advent
DESCRIPTION:The First Sunday of Advent marks the beginning of the Advent season\, the four-week period of preparation and anticipation leading up to Christmas. Advent\, from the Latin adventus meaning 'coming\,' prepares believers to celebrate Christ's birth and await his return.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20321128
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20321129
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:firstlent-2033@christian
SUMMARY:First Day of Lent (Ash Wednesday)
DESCRIPTION:The first day of Lent\, the 40-day season of fasting\, prayer\, and repentance leading up to Resurrection Sunday. Christians receive ashes on their foreheads as a sign of mortality and penitence\, reflecting the words 'Remember that you are dust\, and to dust you shall return.'
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20330302
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20330303
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:nationaldayofprayer-2033@christian
SUMMARY:National Day of Prayer
DESCRIPTION:Observed on the first Thursday of May\, the National Day of Prayer calls people of faith across the United States to unite in prayer for the nation\, its leaders\, and its people. Established by Congress in 1952 and signed into law by President Truman.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20330505
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20330506
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:palmSunday-2033@christian
SUMMARY:Palm Sunday
DESCRIPTION:Palm Sunday marks the beginning of Holy Week and commemorates Jesus Christ's triumphal entry into Jerusalem\, where crowds spread palm branches before him. It falls one week before Resurrection Sunday.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20330410
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20330411
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:goodfriday-2033@christian
SUMMARY:Good Friday
DESCRIPTION:Good Friday commemorates the crucifixion and death of Jesus Christ at Calvary. Observed with solemnity\, fasting\, and special services\, it falls two days before Resurrection Sunday and is one of the most sacred days in the Christian calendar.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20330415
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20330416
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:resurrectionSunday-2033@christian
SUMMARY:Resurrection Sunday
DESCRIPTION:Resurrection Sunday (commonly known as Easter) is the most important celebration in the Christian faith\, commemorating the bodily resurrection of Jesus Christ from the dead on the third day after his crucifixion. It is the foundation of Christian hope and the fulfillment of biblical prophecy.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20330417
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20330418
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ascensionday-2033@christian
SUMMARY:Ascension Day
DESCRIPTION:Ascension Day commemorates the ascension of Jesus Christ into heaven 40 days after his resurrection\, as recorded in Acts 1:9-11. Observed on the 39th day after Resurrection Sunday (the 40th day counting inclusively)\, it marks the end of Christ's post-resurrection appearances.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20330526
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20330527
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pentecost-2033@christian
SUMMARY:Pentecost
DESCRIPTION:Pentecost commemorates the descent of the Holy Spirit upon the apostles and followers of Jesus\, as described in Acts 2\, occurring 50 days after Resurrection Sunday. Often called the birthday of the Church\, it marks the beginning of the Christian mission to the world.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20330605
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20330606
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:reformationday-2033@christian
SUMMARY:Reformation Day
DESCRIPTION:October 31 commemorates Martin Luther's posting of his 95 Theses on the door of the Castle Church in Wittenberg\, Germany\, on October 31\, 1517 — an act widely seen as launching the Protestant Reformation. Observed especially in Lutheran\, Reformed\, and other Protestant traditions.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20331031
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20331101
END:VEVENT

